# Method References

Sometimes a Lambda Expression only calls an existing method.

Instead of

```java
x -> System.out.println(x)
```

we can write

```java
System.out::println
```

This is called a Method Reference.

---

# Types of Method References

```
Method References

│

├── Static Method

├── Instance Method

├── Particular Object Method

└── Constructor Reference
```

---

# Static Method Reference

```java
class Demo {

    static void display() {

        System.out.println("Hello");

    }

}

interface Test {

    void show();

}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Test t = Demo::display;

        t.show();

    }

}
```

---

# Instance Method Reference

```java
class Demo {

    void message() {

        System.out.println("Welcome");

    }

}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Demo d = new Demo();

        Runnable r = d::message;

        r.run();

    }

}
```

---

# Constructor Reference

```java
class Student {

    Student() {

        System.out.println("Constructor");

    }

}

interface Demo {

    Student create();

}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Demo d = Student::new;

        d.create();

    }

}
```

---

# Built-in Functional Interfaces

Java provides many ready-made Functional Interfaces.

```
java.util.function

│

├── Predicate

├── Consumer

├── Supplier

├── Function

├── UnaryOperator

└── BinaryOperator
```

---

# Predicate

Used for testing conditions.

```java
Predicate<Integer> even = n -> n % 2 == 0;

System.out.println(even.test(10));
```

Output

```
true
```

---

# Consumer

Consumes data.

```java
Consumer<String> print = System.out::println;

print.accept("Java");
```

---

# Supplier

Supplies data.

```java
Supplier<Double> random = Math::random;

System.out.println(random.get());
```

---

# Function

Converts one value into another.

```java
Function<String,Integer> length = String::length;

System.out.println(length.apply("Java"));
```

---

# Lambda with Collections

```java
List<String> list = Arrays.asList("Java","Python","C++");

list.forEach(System.out::println);
```

---

# Lambda with Sorting

```java
Collections.sort(list,(a,b)->a.compareTo(b));
```

---

# Lambda with Threads

```java
Thread t = new Thread(() -> {

    System.out.println("Thread Running");

});

t.start();
```

---

# Internal JVM Working

Java does not generate a separate class like Anonymous Classes.

Instead,

the JVM uses

```
invokedynamic
```

instruction.

```
Lambda

    │

    ▼

invokedynamic

    │

    ▼

Runtime Object
```

This improves performance.

---

# Anonymous Class vs Lambda

| Anonymous Class | Lambda |
|-----------------|---------|
| More Code | Less Code |
| Java 1.1 | Java 8 |
| Creates Class | Uses invokedynamic |
| Slower | Faster |
| Verbose | Concise |

---

# Lambda vs Method Reference

| Lambda | Method Reference |
|----------|-----------------|
| `(x)->System.out.println(x)` | `System.out::println` |
| More Flexible | More Readable |

---

